John Edward: Language Skills Required for the Citizens of the World
Independent schools in Scotland are constantly enjoying their scientific achievements - in 2018 they could boast of further outstanding exam results, supported by individual and collective successes in sports, art, music and other social activities.
Featured by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), schools attended by more than 30,000 students across Scotland strive to provide the best level of services provided to students and parents.
Independent schools are designed to prepare students for further and higher education, their chosen career pathways and to indicate their role as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector with the opportunity to develop and implement a curriculum tailored to the needs of the school, we see that modern languages are still popular and desirable subjects to choose from in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to another person in a language that he understands, then it comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it comes to his heart.
This is a clear reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The results of the last exam this year show that the languages take the first place in league rankings, with the highest rates of distance for independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned foreign languages received a higher rating of A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS Member Schools showed that 72% of students received a higher A rating in Mandarin, and 72% of German learners, 69% of French learners, and 63% of Spanish learners also received an A rating.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, learning languages as elective subjects is conducted in the same scope as learning STEM subjects (street sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics) as part of teaching programs in independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 study conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills (UK) found that the lack of language skills of candidates was responsible for the difficulty of employing jobs by employers.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity to prepare young people for starting a career.
These skills are essential in a globalized world with an increasing number of jobs requiring language skills,
Lifelong skills, such as learning a second language, will provide a huge advantage in the future, regardless of the chosen career path.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically increases the chances of a multilingual person in relation to competition.
According to a 2013 survey by YouGov, which involved more than 4,000 UK adults, 75% of them couldn’t speak a foreign language well enough to talk, and the French language was the only language whose percentage of two-digit speakers, i.e. 15%.
Therefore, investing in teaching foreign languages is so important for today’s children.
Knowledge of several languages, in particular the languages of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding the right employment.
In Scotland, each school will differ in terms of the languages taught in it.
Many schools will focus on more classic modern languages, while others will teach languages recognized as the most important for the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the interest of the child, in independent schools there will always be many languages to choose from, which will be taught by specialized teaching staff in this area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a teaching environment that will prepare children and arm them into the skills necessary to succeed, regardless of what the future is preparing for them.
At present, it cannot be denied that in the international business environment, languages are still crucial for the future of the country, so it must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be treated as \"International communication skills\"
Independent schools will continue to offer Scottish youth a great choice, diversity and level.
That's just how it's supposed to be.
John Edward, President of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
