Harvard students attend a course on long-term rest
The new Harvard University course, which took place this year, provided all the students with more sleep, which was aimed at combating the growing culture of macho, consisting in learning by “the all-night students driven by caffeine.”
Academic students from the best university in the world often have no idea of the basics of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
To create the course, he was inspired by his speech on the impact of sleep deprivation on science.
“After the speech, one girl came to me and said, ‘Why am I told this only now that I’m in my last year of study?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” The Telegraph said.
During the course, which took place for the first time this year, it is explained to students how good sleep-related habits help to achieve good results in science and sport, as well as improve the general well-being of students.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Executive Director of the University of Health, said the course was decided to introduce after it was found that students suffered from a severe lack of sleep within a week.
The hourly course includes a number of interactive tasks.
One section includes a picture of a room in an academic room where students click cups for coffee, curtains, exercises and books to get information about the impact of caffeine and light and how sleep deficiency affects sports results, as well as how important it is to maintain sleep regularity.
In another section, participants learn how a long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that this will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have the right to know, just as everyone has the right to know what health effects cigarette smoking brings,” said Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in “all-night science” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students is an increasing problem of lack of sleep.
“Providing enough sleep of good quality should be a secret weapon - students fighting stress, exhaustion and anxiety, and even allowing them to avoid gaining weight because lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, making the student constantly hungry,” he said.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop a course after taking part in some of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to press for a course for the whole campus.
The next step is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar degree program before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler told students to set an alarm resembling when to go to bed and when to get up, and also to be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light,” emitted by the screens of electronic devices and LED lighting, which can blur the period rhythm and lead to trouble sleeping.
