National Trust listens to the secret lives of bats
The new research conducted in the Scottish Highlands is aimed at showing how bats use the landscape when they get food.
The results of the research are expected to shed new light on the preservation of these exceptional flying mammals and help target future actions to protect them.
The research conducted by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will cover common and small dwarfs, as well as brown long-eared bats and bats from the family of reds at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
In key locations around the estate, special recorders will be deployed to monitor the activities of bats all-season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct field research using portable detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings is designed to determine the frequency of signals sent by bats and the manner of behavior of individual species.
A habitat map and a report will then be developed to create a detailed picture of their landscape behavior.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation advisor at NTS, hopes to reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, e.g. the creation of meadows, as well as the best ways to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
The bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have decreased significantly over the last century.
They are at risk of construction and development work, which has an impact on the graves and the loss of habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can also pose a threat, as well as glues on flies and some chemicals used in building materials and even domestic cats.
The bats aren't really blind.
However, due to the nighttime hunting habits of their ears are more helpful than the eyes of the capture.
They use a complex technique of ecolocation to search for worms and obstacles on their way.
The NTS organization, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes bats very seriously.
It consists of ten trained experts who regularly conduct research, inspection of the graves, and sometimes even rescue actions.
The organization has even established Scotland’s first and only dedicated bat reserve in Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten species of bats.
David Thompson, the owner of the estate, says it is ideal for bats.
“Threave has a great area for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, old trees and excellent habitats.
However, there are still many unknowns when it comes to bats. The work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to develop.
It underlines the importance of controls for bats prior to their maintenance work in the estates, as the inadvertent destruction of a single grid can kill up to 400 females and young people, which can lead to the extinction of the entire local population.
The bats are protected - killing, harassment or disturbing them, and destroying their graves is illegal.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to provide assistance.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many species, we don’t even know how their populations manage.
